    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$29.6B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$3.8B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Normalized FCF</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$3.92</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">26.7%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">-${(Math.abs(netCash) / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Debt</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. For utilities with massive debt and capital cycles, normalizing the base year's cash flow is critical to arriving at a grounded valuation.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Normalize Base Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Southern Company's reported FCF for FY2025 was -$2,935M due to $12.7B in capital expenditures. Using a negative base number permanently depresses a DCF. Instead, we take the massive $9.8B in Operating Cash Flow and subtract a sustainable, normalized maintenance CapEx of ~$6.0B, yielding a <strong>normalized base FCF of $3.8 billion</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow the normalized FCF at <strong>5% per year</strong> for 5 years. This aligns with regulated rate base growth and typical utility earnings trajectories following the completion of mega-projects like the Vogtle nuclear units.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.5% forever</strong>. Regulated utilities are slow-growth, steady-state businesses; their long-term growth tends to mirror long-term inflation and GDP expansion.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>7%</strong>. This represents the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) for a utility. With the 10Y Treasury at 4.18% and a low beta (typically around 0.5 for SO), a 7% hurdle rate accurately reflects the low-risk, dividend-heavy nature of the stock.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract net debt, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (-$72.4B) = Equity Value. Utilities carry massive debt loads. Subtracting this massive debt stack from Enterprise Value gives us the value left for shareholders, which is divided by 1.103 billion shares.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Southern Company targets 5% to 7% long-term EPS growth. Given the completion of Plant Vogtle Units 3 and 4, capital intensity will shift towards transmission, distribution, and renewables. A 5% cash flow growth rate is a solid base case for a regulated utility expanding its rate base.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">7%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Utilities have lower required rates of return than tech companies. With a 10Y Treasury of 4.18% and a very low beta, 7% represents a reasonable cost of equity and overall WACC. It compensates investors for the low, albeit very steady, growth profile.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        A utility's terminal growth rate cannot exceed nominal GDP growth. At 2.5%, we model Southern Company keeping pace with long-term inflation, continuing to pass costs through to customers while maintaining its regulated monopoly status.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (Normalized FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025Normalized.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.025)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (7% − 2.5%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
