          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v > 0 ? v : 'N/A'}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Notice that for utilities carrying $74B in debt, small shifts in the discount rate or growth rate can produce wildly different equity valuations. If the discount rate rises to 8-9% (perhaps due to higher Treasury yields), the intrinsic value turns negative, underscoring the leverage risk.</p>

  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What the Model Misses</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Sensitivity:</strong> Utilities are essentially bond proxies. If the 10-Year Treasury yield surges past our 4.18% base, the 7% discount rate will be too low, pushing the intrinsic value down drastically.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Risk:</strong> Southern Company's revenue is heavily dependent on public utility commissions approving rate hikes. If regulators balk at price increases to cover grid modernization or renewables investments, cash flows will suffer.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With over $74B in total debt, Southern Company is highly levered. High debt amplifies both returns and risks; refinancing debt at higher rates could crush margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Execution Risk:</strong> While Vogtle is operational, future mega-projects (like massive transmission buildouts or transitioning coal plants) carry severe cost-overrun risks.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the DCF showing a value below the current stock price?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Regulated utilities often trade at premiums to standard DCF values because the market values their dividend yield and perceived safety more like a bond than a growth equity. Furthermore, our $3.8B normalized FCF might be considered conservative by some analysts.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 7% discount rate instead of 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A 10% discount rate is standard for the broader market (like the S&P 500) and tech companies. Regulated utilities have guaranteed monopolies and very predictable cash flows, making them significantly lower risk (lower beta). Therefore, they command a lower cost of capital (around 6-7.5%).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the reported Free Cash Flow negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Southern Company is incredibly capital-intensive. In FY2025, it generated $9.8B from operations but spent $12.7B on capital expenditures (infrastructure, grid updates, power plants). This negative FCF is why we must use a normalized figure to model the business's true cash-generating power once CapEx normalizes.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

